<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Atriplex confertifolia </i>is a dioecious shrub that reproduces by seed that collects in a seed bank. The mechanisms behind seed germination are unclear, but seed bracts appear to be a mechanical barrier and must break down before seeds can germinate. Shrubs are not typically long-lived. Prolonged drought tends to kill the most mature shrubs. However, following rain, seedlings establish, and stands tend to wax and wane with precipitation patterns. Plants establish readily following mechanical treatments (Simonin 2001a). <br/>
<br/>
Stands make up one of the major regional vegetation types of the Great Basin, and the alliance ranges widely in California. Shrubs exist in low alkali basins, across extensive intermountain flats, and on rocky, upland soils. Plants prefer well-drained, moderately saline soils where groundwater is below the rooting zone. A high chromosomal variation may enable plants to occupy a variety of ecological settings. Diploid individuals grow in rocky uplands; tetraploids typically occur in basins as nearly pure stands. Male plants are much more common on harsher sites than female ones (Simonin 2001a). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
