    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Central California Coast Ranges</b> (M262Ai). Stands occur at Carrizo Plain National Monument.</li>
        
            <li><b>Great Valley</b> (262Ag, Ax, Az). Agricultural development has limited stands to small, scattered sites in the south subsections as a valley sink scrub (Holland 1986).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa, Ac-d, Af-h, Aj, Al). Stands include both upland and basin settings in this section. In northern subsections, stands occur on upland rocky hills, intermixed with those of <i>Ambrosia dumosa, Ephedra nevadensis, Larrea tridentata, Menodora spinescens, Yucca brevifolia,</i> and <i>Yucca schidigera</i> alliances. Stands also occur in valleys, on low dunes, and on flats surrounding and the edges of alkali basins and playas. Most stands in the southern areas are in valleys adjacent to <i>Atriplex polycarpa</i> stands and below other upland stands of <i>Larrea tridentata</i> and <i>Ambrosia dumosa.</i> The alliance ranges up to the <i>Artemisia tridentata-Pinus monophylla</i> zone at higher elevations (Thomas et al. 2004) and to shallow, eroded sand fields adjacent to the playas of Edwards Air Force Base (Charlton 2000a).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341De-f, Dh-j). Stands are around Mono Lake and upper Chalfant Valley and on flats near Crowley Lake.</li>
        
            <li><b>Northwestern Basin and Range</b> (342Ba-d). Large stands exist in the Surprise Valley, east of the Alkali Lakes area, and on the north shore of Honey Lake. They mix with those of the <i>Sarcobatus vermiculatus</i> and <i>Suaeda moquinii</i> alliances near the margins of playas. Monospecific stands occur on lower and middle bajadas.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Es). Scattered stands occupy basins of the Piute and Tehachapi mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fa-f). Upland stands are extensive in northern subsections where they mix with stands of the <i>Artemisia tridentata, Grayia spinosa, Larrea tridentata-Ambrosia dumosa,</i> and <i>Yucca brevifolia</i> alliances. Upland stands in Saline Valley area show a recent decline (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Atriplex confertifolia </i>stands occupy a broad spectrum of environmental situations. They may be seral and invasive, short-lived, or natural and persistent. In many parts of its range, <i>A. confertifolia </i>may tolerate moderate to heavy grazing because of its spinescent habit, except in years of lower than average precipitation. Increases in <i>A. confertifolia </i>relative to other desert shrubs in grazed sites are generally the result of decreased competition from more heavily browsed associates. However, the overall presence of non-native annuals may also increase in these grazed sites (Simonin 2001a). We need further information to understand the allianceâ€™s ecology in California, especially in terms of the presence of non-native grasses and response to fire. </div>
</div>

    

    

